skos:Concept.skos:definition: جدار (أنظر التعريف) منشأ بعدد من الخلايا، أي فتحات. أي أن الجدار يتكون من منشآت متجاورة على امتداد واحد
A wall (see definition there) constructed of multiple 'cells', i.e. with openings. In effect, the wall is formed of adjoining structures in a linear arrangement.

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: was present at / the location of
ركام متناثر/ أجزاء من عناصر معمارية

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: other than RCU

skos:Concept.skos:definition: موظفون في مشروع إيديها و/ أو آر سي يو، ويشمل ذلك موظفي المراحل الأولى والثانية والثالثة، وكذلك المتعاقدين بعقود مؤقتة
skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: مشروع إيديها/ موظفي آر سي يو
skos:Concept.skos:definition: Staff of the IDIHA project and/or the RCU. Includes all stream 1, 2, and 3 staff, also if on temporary contracts.

skos:Concept.skos:altLabel: is referred to in / refers to

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: The dispersal/spread of archaeological material/objects across the surface or subsurface of an archaeological site. This is often the result of ploughing.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: The release of energy in an often sudden and violent way. This can lead to the sudden shattering or blowing apart of objects/features.
إطلاق طاقة بشكل مفاجئ وعنيف. وقد يؤدي ذلك إلى تصدّع مفاجئ أو التناثر للقطع أو الملامح
انهيار أو حركة كتلة من التربة أو الصخر، وعادة ما تكون الحركة لأسفل بإتجاه مائل
The collapse/movement of a mass of earth or rock, generally down a slope.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: The risk of damage caused to archaeological sites/features via fire. This can include both risk of damage caused by the flames of the fire, as well as risk of smoke damage.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Feature in the shape of the serif capital letter 'I', including wider 'bars' at the ends.

The act of digging or creating a hole/trench with heavy duty machinery for a purpose other than mining/quarrying. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting.
عملية الحفر، أو عمل حفرة/خندق باستخدام المعدات الثقيلة لأهداف غير استخراج الحجر أو استخراج المعادن. ويشمل هذا المصطلح الحفائر الأثرية، أو الحفر من أجل نهب الدفائن.

This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of bodies of water (i.e. sea, lake, river, 'wadi') and/or by the flow and movement of the wind, but where it is uncertain which of the two or both were responsible.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: The deliberate removal and relocation of archaeological features from one site to another. This may be done to protect archaeological features (e.g. prevent its destruction via inundation etc.) or for other reasons.
Ceramics

skos:Concept.skos:definition: سكة تقود من مكان إلى مكان آخر، وعادة ما يكون قد تم تمهيده أو تعديله، إو معالجة سطحه بواسطة الإنسان
A path or route leading from one place to another, often including a built or anthropogenically modified/altered surface
Changes in the shape/form of landforms or the topography of a site as the result of activities, such as the bulldozing/dumping of non-local material.
The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth, by unknown means
استخراج الموارد الطبيعية/ والمواد الجيولوجية، مثل المعادن، والحجر وغير ذلك من الأرض بوسائل غير معروفة

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: التدخل لدى المالك/ الشاغل/ السكان المحليين

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: For use with "No Visible/Known"

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A cairn of tower-like construction, circular or quadrangular, clearly recognisable by the presence of masonry, that may contain or cover burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature.
التواجد لبساتين أو غابات تمت زراعتها بواسطة الإنسان
The presence of anthropogenically planted and/or managed orchards, forests and/or woods (silviculture).

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: قائمة اليونسكو للتراث العالمي المعرض للخطر
UNESCO World Heritage in Danger List
Saudi Commission for Tourism and National Heritage (SCTH)
الهيئة العامة للسياحة والتراث الوطني السعودية
UCL Institute of Archaeology Special Collections
CORONA Atlas of the Middle East, Center for Advanced Spatial Technologies, University of Arkansas
Aerial Photographic Archive for Archaeology in the Middle East (APAAME)
The African Rock Art Image Project
Sir Aurel Stein Archive, The British Academy Library and Archive
The British Academy Library and Archive
Air Survey Photographs, UCL Institute of Archaeology Special Collections
Historic Environment Image Resource, University of Oxford (HEIR)
Endangered Archaeology in the Middle East and North Africa (EAMENA)

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A tower tomb (see definition) surrounded by one or more concentric steps. There is no gap between the central tower and the surrounding steps.
A concentration of stones forming a substantial mound, more than 2 m in diameter and 30 cm in height. Anything smaller falls into the “Stone pile” category.
تجمع أحجار يشكل تل يزيد قطره عن مترين وارتفاعه يزيد على 30 سنتيمتر، أي تجمع أحجار أصغر يتم تصنيفه على أنه مجموعة أحجار

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: اختلاف في اللون/ اختلاف في الملمس

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A man-made level surface designed to create a level area for a particular purpose, e.g. agriculture.
Man-made raised surface designed to create an even, generally level area for a particular purpose, e.g. the construction of a building.
مساحة مستوية مرتفعة عن سطح الأرض من صنع الإنسان، صممت لوظيفة معينة مثل بناء مبنى
Man-made raised or constructed surface where one end is built higher than its opposite end, creating an even, but sloping platform.
A small concentration of stones with no visible architectural organisation (no masonry or stone alignments) up to 2 m in diameter and 30 cm in height. Anything bigger falls into the “Cairn” category.
تجمع صغير لأحجار دون تصميم معماري معين (ليس بناء، ولا استقامة على إمتداد واحد) بقطر حتى مترين وارتفاع حتى 30 سنتيمتر، وكل ما هو أكبر يصنف على أنه "كومة" المذكورة عاليه.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: Relating to the use of a site/place for communication and/or artistic purposes.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Social factors that contribute to deterioration processes of the fabric of heritage sites. Some uses might have a positive impact as they enhance certain values while others might compromise ascribed values and could lead to the deterioration of the heritage site. "Religious" is technically part of this, but is distinguished separately in this database.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: For use with "No Visible/Known"

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Relating to the deliberate destruction or damage to public or private property, without obvious reason.

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: Aerial Photographic Archive for Archaeology in the Middle East (APAAME)
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)
Development of Conservation and Management Plan

skos:Concept.skos:definition: The act of animals consuming vegetation/and or being moved across an area of land whether that vegetation be natural or planted.
العملية التي تستهلك بموجبها الحيوانات الزرع، وقد يكون ذلك بحركة الحيوانات خلال مساحة من الأرض بغض النظر عن كون هذا الزرع قد نمى طبيعياً، أو قد تمت زراعته
يشمل هذا المصطلح عدة تأثيرات كالتآكل والبري، والذي يسببه تدفق وحركة الرياح. ولا تشمل تغيرات الحرارة والرطوبة واللتان تم تسجيلهما كمسببات مختلفة

This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of the wind. It does not include temperature and humidity changes which are listed as a separate cause.

To upgrade a building, or parts of it, with newer finish materials, furniture, fixtures, or equipment. To only include activities which do not fall under construction e.g. adding electricity, painting, replacing old water pipes.
يشمل هذا المصطلح عدة تأثيرات كالتآكل والبري، والذي يسببه تدفق وحركة محتويات مائية (مثل البحر، أو البحيرة، أو النهر، أو الوادي). ولا يشمل الفيضان ولا الترسيب واللذان تم تسجيلهما كمسببات مختلفة

This term covers a series of effects (e.g. erosion/weathering) which are caused by the flow and movement of bodies of water (i.e. sea, lake, river, 'wadi'). It does not include flooding and precipitation which are listed as separate causes.

Shifts in the environmental conditions at a site/of a feature. This definition would include changes in moisture content at both a local and regional level, as well as shifts in the comparative scales of hot and cold.
نقلة في الأحوال المناخية للموقع أو الملمح. يشمل هذا التعريف التغيرات في محتوى الرطوبة سواء على المستوى المحلي أو المستوى الاقليمي، وكذلك التغيرات على مقاييس الحرارة والبرودة.

The act of trying to keep archaeological sites in good condition, possibly through the addition of modern features, such as walkways etc. on a heritage site. It includes the implementation of upkeep and maintenance activities to look after sites. This category also includes both implementation of tourism and management strategies (such as the addition of modern features e.g. walkways, dedication of human resources and development of conservation plans, etc.) on a heritage site. This does not, however, include actual conservation activities for which there is a separate term.
محاولات حفظ المواقع الأثري في حالة جيدة، ويمكن أن يكون ذلك من خلال إضافة ملامح حديثة، مثل الممرات، وغير ذلك بالموقع التراثي. ولا يشمل ذلك الحفاظ needs to be adjusted
The act of living, inhabiting or continuing to utilise a certain place
عملية الحياة، أو السكن أو الاستخدام المتواصل لمكان معين.
عملية طبيعية تشمل طفح محتوى مائي خارج حدوده المعتادة، مما يؤدي إلى غمر الملامح الأثرية بالماء أو إغراقها تجت المحتوى المائي. ويجب التفريق بين هذا المصطلح وبين مصطلح "غمر"

A natural act involving an overflow from a water body, beyond its normal limits. This can lead to archaeological features being covered or submerged under a body of water. This term is differentiated from inundation
The act of destruction or tearing down of archaeological structures. This act can be carried out both in a controlled and uncontrolled manner, but also using both mechanised and/or hand machinery
عملية هدم أو إزالة منشأ أثري. تتم هذه العملية بأسلوب فيه تحكم، أو بأسلوب ليس به تحكم، وقد تكون بشكل يدوي أو بشكل آلي
عملية تغطية مساحة معينة بالماء، وتختلف عن الفيضان في كون الغمر يتم بفعل الإنسان
An anthropogenic act involving an area being covered/overwhelmed with water. This is differentiated from flooding by being defined as a deliberate and anthropogenic act.
The violent discharge of steam/volcanic material from an active vent in the earth's crust
النفث العنيف لبخار أو مواد بركانية من فتحة نشطة بالقشرة الأرضية
التغيير المتعمد لمستويات التربة أو سطح الأرض. قد يشمل ذلك تنسيق المواقع بهدف عمل مدرجات، أو وضع تربة مستقدمة من مكان آخر لرفع منسوب سطح الأرض

The delibreate act of changing the contours of the land/earth's surface. This can include landscaping in order to produce terraces, as well as the deposition of imported soil, raising the level of land surface/
عملية البناء، وتشمل المنشآت مثل البيوت، والبنية التحتية وغيرها. قد تكون هذه العمليات بمقاييس صناعية، أو كأعمال عامة، وقد تكون بمقياس أصغر بكثير على مستوى المسكن

The act of building, including structures, such as housing, infrastructure etc., and the resulting product/s. These activities can be on an industrial/public scale, or at a much smaller 'domestic' scale.
عملية إحداث ثقب باستخدام آلية ثاقبة أو دورانية، ترتبط عملية الثقب بأنشطة معينة مثل استخراج البترول وحفر آبار المياه
The act of making a hole using a boring or rotating mechanism. Drilling can be associated with activities such as Oil extraction and the sinking of well systems.
An exothermic process involving the oxidation of material, sending out light and heat and possibly producing smoke.
عملية إكسوثرمية تشمل أكسدة المواد، وإطلاق ضوء وحرارة مع احتمال أن ينتج دخان
The returning of a place to a known earlier state by removing accretions or by reassembling existing elements without the introduction of new material.
The act of turning/breaking up the earth, predominantly in preparation for the planting of crops.
عملية تقليب/ أو تفتيت التربة، بهدف التحضير لزراعة المحاصيل.

الفعل الذي يهدف إلى منع أو تقليل فقد المادة الأثرية باستخدام منهجيات علمية لا يشمل ذلك الأعمال أو الإجراءات الخاصة بالإبقاء على الدخول للموقع أو المماشي وغيرها، ضمن إجراءات تقديم الموقع للسياح إلى غير ذلك.

The act of trying to prevent or limit the loss of archaeological material using scientific methods. This does not cover actions or processes that attempt to maintain access to or create walkways etc. as a way of maintaining archaeological sites for tourism etc.
Presence of non-moving objects used in transport e.g. cars, tanks etc., at a site. For example, the presence of stationary tanks may indicate that the site is under military control.
وجود عناصر غير متحركة، كالسيارات، والدبابات، وغيرها في الموقع. فعلى سبيل المثال، وجود دبابة غير متحركة قد يشير إلى أن الموقع تحت السيطرة العسكرية.

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: سرقة/ إزالة غير مسموح بها للقطع
skos:Concept.skos:definition: Removal of non-structural items (for structural use structural robbing) e.g immovable objects, site panels or signage. record when signage is stolen from a site or items from a museum. Note: use "Excavation" linked to "Looting" when looter's holes are seen but you do not definitely know that material has been removed from the site.
An explosive charge laid on or just under a surface (anthropogenic or natural)
(عبوة ناسفة فوق الأرض أو تحت سطح الأرض مباشرة (بواسطة الإنسان أو بشكل طبيعي
The act of firing or letting off small scale weaponry e.g. guns as opposed to the use of artillery.
عملية إطلاق النار باستخدام أسلح خفيفة، مثل البنادق (وليس المدفعية الثقيلة)
عملية نقل أو نزع مواد كالحجر أو الطوب الطيني من موقع أثري
The act of removing material (e.g. stone/mudbrick) from an archaeological site.
إفساد أو تلويث الأرض، أو الماء، أو الهواء، عن طريق وجود أو إدخال مواد مضرة أو سامة. يشمل ذلك التلوث الناتج عن الكوارث الطبيعية، كما يشمل التلوث الذي تسببه المناطق الحضرية العالية الكثافة، وغير ذلك.

The contamination of the land, water, air etc., by the presence or introduction of poisioness or harmful substances. This can cover pollution arising from natural disasters, as well as pollution caused by dense urbanization etc.
عملية إعادة بناء موقع أثري بعد أن حدث به تدمير. وفي هذه الحالة، يشمل المصطلح كلا من المواقع التي تم استخدام المواد الأصلية لإعادة إنشائها، وتلك التي تم الخلط بها، أو التي تم إضافة مواد حديثة لها.

The act of rebuilding an archaeological site or a place to its known and earlier state that was damaged or destroyed . In this case, the definition includes sites where both the original materials have been used and those in reconstruction where a mixture or additional "modern" and new materials and techniques are used. It is distinguished from "Restoration" by this use of new materials.
استخراج الموارد الطبيعية/ والمواد الجيولوجية، مثل المعادن، والحجر وغير ذلك من الأرض بالحفر تحت سطح الأرض، ويتم الوصول إليه عن طريق أنفاق، وفتحات أو كهوف.
The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by excavating under the surface of the ground, accessed through tunnels, shafts, or caves.
استخراج الموارد الطبيعية/ والمواد الجيولوجية، مثل المعادن، والحجر وغير ذلك من الأرض بواسطة الكشط أو معالجة سطح الأرض، وعادة ما يتم ذلك بمعدات مثل الجرافة (البولدوزر)، وعادة في سياق طميي/ غريني

The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by scraping or working the surface of the ground, often with machinery such as bulldozers. Most often in alluvial contexts.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: Invasion/inhabitation by living organisms in numbers or quantities large enough to be harmful. This includes burrowing.
skos:Concept.skos:definition: هجوم/استيطان بواسطة كائنات حية بأعداد وكميات كبيرة مما يجعلها مضرة، وهذا يشمل إقامة الجحور
توفير الماء بشكل متعمد ومن صنع الإنسان عن طريق مواسير، أو رشاشات، أو مصارف، أو قنوات
The artificial and deliberate provision of water by the means of pipes, sprinklers, drains, ditches etc.
التخلص من المواد غير المرغوب فيها، شاملاً بقايا المواد، والنفايات
The action of disposing of unwanted material, including scrap material and waste.
The act of deliberate breaking and damage of heritage.
عملية حفر وإيجاد أنفاق خلال الأرض أو الصخر. وعادة ما ترتبط هذه العملية بالتعدين أو بإنشاء عناصر هيدرولوجية.
The act of creating/digging a usually narrow passage or channel through earth/rock. This process can be connected with mining activities and the construction of hydrological features.
تركيب واستخدام نظام ري مرتكز على محور يدور حول مركز دائرة لتوفير المياه لمنطقة
The installation and use of a centre pivot irrigation system for the provision of water to an area.
عملية الحفر، أو عمل حفرة/خندق باليد أو بمعدات يدوية لأهداف غير استخراج الحجر أو استخراج المعادن. ويشمل هذا المصطلح الحفائر الأثرية، أو الحفر من أجل نهب الدفائن.

The act of digging or creating a hole/trench by hand/hand tools for a purpose other than mining/quarrying. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting.
عملية إخلاء و/أو تسوية/ هدم الأرض أو الملامح الأثرية/ المباني الحديثة إلخ، باستخدام الآلات الميكانيكية
The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., using mechanised machinery.
Sudden movement/vibrations of the earth's crust e.g. earthquakes
الحركة أو الذبذبة المفاجئة لقشرة الأرض، مثل الزلازل

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: (استخراج الحجر/ استخراج المعادن (خندق مفتوح/ حفرة مفتوحة
skos:Concept.skos:definition: استخراج الموارد الطبيعية/ والمواد الجيولوجية، مثل المعادن، والحجر وغير ذلك من الأرض بحفر آبار وخنادق على سطح الأرض
The extraction of natural resources/geological materials i.e. metals, stone etc. from the earth by excavating pits or trenches into the surface.
Cultivated or natural plant cover
زروع نمت بشكل طبيعي أو زرعها الإنسان
عملية إخلاء و/أو تسوية/ هدم الأرض أو الملامح الأثرية/ المباني الحديثة إلخ، باسلوب يدوي
The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., by hand/using handtools.
سكة، أو شبكة من السكك التي يسير عليها القطار. وتكون عبارة عن قضبان حديدية ممتدة على الأرض.
A track or network of tracks along which a train runs. Usually composed of a series of steel rails running along the ground.

The act of digging or creating a hole/trench for a purpose other than mining/quarrying where it is not clear whether this has been carried out using mechanised machinery or by hand. This term can be used to cover archaeological excavation or excavation for the purposes of looting.

عملية الحفر، أو عمل حفرة/خندق. إلا أنه ليس من الواضح إن كان قد تم باليد أو بمعدات يدوية أو باستخدام المعدات الثقيلة، لأهداف غير استخراج الحجر أو استخراج المعادن. ويشمل هذا المصطلح الحفائر الأثرية، أو الحفر من أجل نهب الدفائن.
عملية إخلاء و/أو تسوية/ هدم الأرض أو الملامح الأثرية/ المباني الحديثة إلخ، في حالة عدم وضوح ما إذا كانت هذه العملية قد تمت يدوياً أو آلياً

The act of clearing and/or flattening/destroying ground or archaeological features/modern buildings etc., where it is not clear whether this has been carried out using mechanised machinery or by hand.
تكثيف بخار الماء في الغلاف الجوي والذي ينتج عنه الماء الذي يسقط في صورة أمطار، أو ثلوج، أو المطر المتجمد، وغير ذلك، والذي يتم تجمعه على سطح الأرض.
The condensation of water vapour in the earth's atmosphere which leads to water falling in the form of rain, snow, sleet etc. and being deposited on the earth's surface.
The act of people moving across a heritage site, which can cause damage to the features and erosion.
عملية حفر خنادق في الأرض الطبيعية لتوفير المياه لمنطقة ما أو ضمن منظومة ري
The act of digging trenches across a landscape and the provision of water through that system to an area.
عملية الكتابة أو الرسم (قد يكون بالخدش، أو الطلاء، أو غيرها) على سطح. وفي هذا السياق يكون السطح لقطعة أثرية، أو ملمح أثري، أو موقع أثري
The act of writing or drawing (can be scratched, painted etc.) something onto a surface. In this case the surface of an archaeological object, feature or site.
يستخدم هذا المصطلح للدلالة على أنه، في ظل الأدلة المتاحة، لا يوجد ما يدل على ضرر/ أو مخاطر تواجه الموقع الأثري المذكور في صورة منشورة أو مصادر مرئية محددة.

This term should be used to indicate that, given the current evidence, there is no evidence for damage and/or threat to the archaeological site mentioned in published imagery or identifiable from imagery sources.

skos:Concept.skos:prefLabel: إنعدام الصيانة/ الإدارة/ الإجراءات والنشاطات القانونية
Lack of Maintenance/Management/Legal Measures and Activities
skos:Concept.skos:definition: Lack of upkeep activities, and legal frameworks (e.g legal enforcement of protection of heritage places) to look after sites. This category also includes lack of tourism and management strategies (such as the lack of human and financial resources and conservation plan, etc.) on a heritage site.
Feature in the shape of the letter 'U', i.e. with three closed sides and one open side.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: Relating to the use of a site/place for communication and/or artistic purposes (e.g. rock art).
The dispersal/spread of archaeological material/objects across the surface or subsurface of an archaeological site. This is often the result of ploughing.
65 BCE to 450 CE

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A cairn of tower-like construction (see feature form definition for tower), clearly recognisable by the presence of masonry, that may contain or cover burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature, and surrounded by an outer ring of masonry. The space between the inner tower and outer ring is filled with stone and/or sediment at least up to a certain height.

Archaeological Activity: The non intrusive and intrusive processes by which information is collected about the location, distribution and organisation of past human activities. The approaches can be either extensive or intensive depending the objectives that need to be addressed. Heritage Activity: Programmes of research that seek to identify the archaeological and/or architectural significance of a site or landscape.

A field and desk based assessment of heritage condition and vulnerability so that informed decisions can be made regarding how best to preserve, and manage the heritage resource. The preventive activities aimed at avoiding and minimizing future deterioration or loss. These measures are indirect – they do not interfere with the materials and structures of the heritage. They do not modify their appearance.
A general term for the weatherproof coat on the external and internal walls of a building. It is used both as protective and decorative layer.

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: The process of archaeological material being worn away/weathered, often due to natural causes (exposure to wind, rain, sunlight, as well as salt crystalization, insects and pests damage, and growth of micro-organisms).

Cracks will occur as a result of stress to structures. Cracks that occur within a limited/small area will not cause structural instability, however from fractures rainwater enters the structure and also plants and vegetation are often starts to grow-out resulting into structural damage and destabilization. Recording and monitoring of cracks is an important step to understand whether they are enlarging or any deformation is in progress.

To be used when there is no (obvious) damage to the site or feature, but the visual aspect of the heritage is altered. For example with electricity cables running over a wall, or a large shelter built over the site.
The drainage/percolation of harmful chemicals/waste materials into the soils of an archaeological site.
Powdering of renders or surface finishing.
The damage caused to archaeological sites/features via fire. This can include both damage caused by the flames of the fire, as well as smoke damage.

Deposits burying/concealing features of archaeological significance, this can include the effects of sedimentation, rock falls, dumping of non-local material and/or the erection of new buildings or structures. It also covers sites that are only partially covered.
The pressing or packing down of archaeological sites/artefacts/soils and so the material becomes flattened and/or compressed.
Changes in the shape/form of landforms or the topography of a site as the result of activities, such as the bulldozing/dumping of non-local material.
Only to use when the cause is "No Visible/Known".
The removal of archaeological material from a site, often resulting from activities such as looting or archaeological excavation.

Damage causing archaeological sites or features to fall in/subside or to become structurally unsound, or the structural integrity of the site or feature to be compromised. This may include the partial or full demolition/destruction of a site or feature. This category includes structural deformation, inclination and swelling.

The limiting of movement into and around an archaeological site. This can be due to activities such as inundation, as well as occupation/use of the site for military purposes.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A simple structure (of no ostentatious or monumental character) or pit/depression designed to house or mark human (or animal) remains.
A wall used to retain soil for agricultural or other purposes.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: A tomb/grave/burial surrounded by an outer ring of stones, that may/may not be covered by small stone pile or cairn. There is gap between the tomb/grave/burial and the outer ring (bedrock or ground surface visible).

An enclosure structure composed of three or more clearly distinct spaces (courtyard/cell) in a complex organization. This type of enclosure encompasses “compound” like organizations, as well as sometimes extended layouts stretching over wide areas (up to 200 m in length). They might reflect more permanent (semi-permanent, sedentary) settlement types.

Or 'pendant tail'. A linear arrangement or 'tail' made of elongated and linear mounds of stones, masoned structures, stone piles, or a masonry wall with internal compartments (other varieties are possible).

An enclosure structure composed of two clearly distinct spaces (courtyard/cell) in a consistent structure entity. This type of enclosure is most likely to constitute a temporary pastoral nomadic base camp grouping the dwelling and herding functions in a single structure.
Painted object or surface. Specialisation of "Inscription/Rock Art/Relief".
A mound of earth and/or stones that may contain burial(s) or remains interred in a built hollow or feature.

A complex arrangement of cairns and/or walls which form the shape of a 'gate', i.e. 2 or more long parallel walls/arrangement of cairns, bounded at both ends by a more substantial wall/group of cairns.

skos:Concept.skos:definition: Inscribed object or surface. Specialisation of "Inscription/Rock Art/Relief".
A cairn (see feature form definition) hosting a tomb in a natural cavity, covered by a heap of stones or surrounded by a semi-circular stone construction abutted to the outcrop.
An object used for games or leisure, only to be used for open air versions (e.g. rock-cut depressions).

An enclosure structure composed of a single space (of a courtyard type, mostly unroofed) delimitated by a wall or alignment of stones. This type of enclosure would encompass corrals and pens intended to park domesticated animal herds.
Carved object or surface. Specialisation of "Inscription/Rock Art/Relief".
A stepped tower tomb (see definition) surrounded by an outer ring of stones. There is a gap between the inner tower and outer ring (bedrock or ground surface visible).

Archaeological field survey incorporates a range of methods leading to the detection, identification and documentation of the material traces of past human activity. Survey collects information about the location, distribution and organisation of past human cultures across a given study area. Excavation is the exposure, processing and recording of archaeological remains. Survey generally proceeds and complements excavation, and is external and horizontal in extent whereas excavation is internal and vertical.
